38
00:02:16,059 --> 00:02:17,499
You can't really get your hands on.

39
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:19,621
And quite frankly, neither can the law.

40
00:02:20,201 --> 00:02:24,024
So there are a lot of different considerations

41
00:02:24,104 --> 00:02:25,825
that come into play whenever we're

42
00:02:25,845 --> 00:02:27,486
talking about intellectual property.

43
00:02:27,946 --> 00:02:29,947
And the most common answer you will ever

44
00:02:30,067 --> 00:02:33,389
hear to any question you ask any lawyer is going to be,

45
00:02:33,489 --> 00:02:33,950
it depends.

46
00:02:34,897 --> 00:02:35,878
I'm sorry, it depends.

47
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:39,924
There is no yes or no when it comes to intellectual property

48
00:02:39,944 --> 00:02:40,165
law.

49
00:02:40,185 --> 00:02:43,069
So everything is going to be on a case by case basis.

50
00:02:47,127 --> 00:02:49,508
There are certain types of IP, obviously.

51
00:02:49,549 --> 00:02:51,690
I think most people are probably pretty familiar

52
00:02:51,710 --> 00:02:54,292
with the big three, which is copyright, trademark, patent.

53
00:02:54,732 --> 00:02:56,294
These are the ones that we always hear about.

54
00:02:56,334 --> 00:02:57,635
It's part of the TRIPS agreement.

55
00:02:57,695 --> 00:03:00,137
It's something that you see talked about every day

56
00:03:00,197 --> 00:03:02,598
when we hear about, you know, trademark issues

57
00:03:02,638 --> 00:03:05,981
in the King case, patent trolls, things like that.

58
00:03:06,762 --> 00:03:10,284
But there are also a lot of non-federal IP issues

59
00:03:10,324 --> 00:03:11,625
that come into play, and, you know.

60
00:03:12,126 --> 00:03:21,018
So the ones that don't really get talked about as much, although there has been some issues recently with the whole Oculus Rift trade secret issue.

61
00:03:22,440 --> 00:03:24,703
By and large, they don't really get as much attention as they should.

62
00:03:25,384 --> 00:03:29,249
And that's kind of a problem because when it comes down to cases, literally...

63
00:03:30,434 --> 00:03:36,718
A common law case for a name and likeness or defamation issue is going to be just as costly

64
00:03:36,779 --> 00:03:38,760
and troublesome as a copyright claim.

65
00:03:39,561 --> 00:03:43,964
So it's important to bear in mind that the entire body of intellectual property law is something

66
00:03:43,984 --> 00:03:45,265
that you need to be mindful of.

67
00:03:47,967 --> 00:03:50,629
So first question is, what is copyright?

68
00:03:50,689 --> 00:03:55,973
You have the textbook explanation here, which is why I want to briefly look it over.

69
00:03:56,730 --> 00:04:02,132
The one thing that you really need to pay attention to here is that original does not necessarily mean unique.

70
00:04:03,072 --> 00:04:09,233
Just because it's something that you've created originally, there is something called independent origin,

71
00:04:09,273 --> 00:04:16,375
which means that two people can create identical works so long as neither one has access to one another.

72
00:04:16,415 --> 00:04:17,875
There is no copyright infringement.

73
00:04:18,215 --> 00:04:21,396
So that's something to bear in mind. Original does not mean unique.

74
00:04:24,891 --> 00:04:29,053
And the other thing that you absolutely have to pay attention to with this is it has to be fixed.

75
00:04:29,113 --> 00:04:31,735
It actually has to be in some sort of physical medium.

76
00:04:31,795 --> 00:04:38,118
You have to be able to physically touch it or see it or have some record of your work.

77
00:04:40,959 --> 00:04:44,061
So what are copyrights?

78
00:04:44,101 --> 00:04:47,863
This is kind of the plain English version of what copyrights are.

79
00:04:48,783 --> 00:04:49,764
It goes beyond Eureka.

80
00:04:50,691 --> 00:04:52,092
One of the most dangerous things,

81
00:04:52,112 --> 00:04:53,633
a thing that I hear all too often,

82
00:04:54,193 --> 00:04:56,694
one of the most dangerous things a developer can say is,

83
00:04:56,974 --> 00:04:58,615
let me tell you my game idea,

84
00:04:59,115 --> 00:05:00,556
whenever they haven't done anything with it.

85
00:05:01,236 --> 00:05:02,057
And the reason that is,

86
00:05:02,077 --> 00:05:05,038
is because there is no protection for your idea,

87
00:05:05,058 --> 00:05:07,319
especially if you're broadcasting it.

88
00:05:08,520 --> 00:05:09,680
There is no copyright protection,

89
00:05:09,720 --> 00:05:10,761
there is no trademark protection.

90
00:05:11,907 --> 00:05:15,228
But you don't have any real protections for your ideas.

91
00:05:15,328 --> 00:05:17,730
So let me tell you about my game idea.

92
00:05:17,770 --> 00:05:20,471
It's not something that you ever want to say as a developer.

93
00:05:22,312 --> 00:05:27,795
As far as the methods of fixation, as you can see,

94
00:05:27,815 --> 00:05:29,155
you have books, saved documents.

95
00:05:30,556 --> 00:05:33,678
It's so long as you have some record

96
00:05:33,798 --> 00:05:35,418
of your copyrighted work, something

97
00:05:35,438 --> 00:05:37,399
that you can submit to the copyright office

98
00:05:37,439 --> 00:05:38,420
if you decide to register.

99
00:05:39,780 --> 00:05:42,921
you will be protected so long as it's obviously not infringing.

100
00:05:42,961 --> 00:05:44,421
It has to be for a legal purpose.

101
00:05:45,062 --> 00:05:46,582
So that's another thing to keep in mind.

102
00:05:47,242 --> 00:05:49,743
If your work is in and of itself infringing,

103
00:05:51,364 --> 00:05:54,745
you're probably not going to obtain the types of protections

104
00:05:54,805 --> 00:05:55,325
that you want.

105
00:05:58,277 --> 00:05:59,697
So what copyright is not?

106
00:05:59,737 --> 00:06:01,058
As I said, it's not your idea.

107
00:06:01,278 --> 00:06:03,098
This is an issue that I have to harp on a lot,

108
00:06:03,238 --> 00:06:08,099
because this is the most common area where people get confused.

109
00:06:08,199 --> 00:06:09,159
Like, this is my idea.

110
00:06:09,219 --> 00:06:10,299
They stole my idea.

111
00:06:10,599 --> 00:06:12,060
Isn't it protected by copyright?

112
00:06:12,380 --> 00:06:14,100
Well, no, it's not, unless you've actually

113
00:06:14,140 --> 00:06:15,140
done something with it.

114
00:06:16,240 --> 00:06:17,681
And even a treatment, things like that.

115
00:06:18,121 --> 00:06:20,161
And what I mean by treatment, if you're not quite familiar,

116
00:06:20,181 --> 00:06:25,302
it's basically like a summary or a design document,

117
00:06:26,042 --> 00:06:26,642
a good example.

118
00:06:27,103 --> 00:06:30,965
Something like that can give you the requisite copyright protection that you need.

119
00:06:31,266 --> 00:06:36,569
But until you've taken your work or your idea to that stage, you're not going to be entitled

120
00:06:36,589 --> 00:06:38,531
to the type of protection that you probably want.

121
00:06:41,793 --> 00:06:46,796
As far as what else it is, it can't be something that you can use.

122
00:06:48,617 --> 00:06:49,518
It can't be useful.

123
00:06:49,578 --> 00:06:55,802
It can't be a product or service, for example.

124
00:06:56,547 --> 00:07:01,910
It has to be something that is purely creative and useless,

125
00:07:03,951 --> 00:07:08,573
in the simplest way to put it.

126
00:07:09,133 --> 00:07:12,935
And I don't want people to get confused by this.

127
00:07:13,255 --> 00:07:17,837
What I mean by that is that you can have creative components in a useful product.

128
00:07:19,137 --> 00:07:19,738
For example...

129
00:07:20,427 --> 00:07:24,549
The Coke bottle is a good example of a lot of things.

130
00:07:25,629 --> 00:07:34,493
And one of the ways is the actual design of the Coke bottle itself is separable from the function of the Coke bottle.

131
00:07:34,973 --> 00:07:43,477
So to a certain extent, maybe not copyright, but there are going to be certain protections to that design itself that you're going to want to,

132
00:07:44,258 --> 00:07:45,978
that you need to take into consideration whenever.

133
00:07:50,465 --> 00:07:52,787
So another thing, it's not perpetual.

134
00:07:54,769 --> 00:07:58,391
You do have a limited term. So 90 years from the life of the author.

135
00:07:59,272 --> 00:08:00,213
120 years from publication.

136
00:08:03,896 --> 00:08:06,338
Oh, what I was going to say about the usefulness.

137
00:08:07,158 --> 00:08:10,481
A good example, probably the best example that we can talk about here

138
00:08:10,901 --> 00:08:13,563
is game mechanics versus the creative content of a game.

139
00:08:14,484 --> 00:08:17,026
So the mechanics themselves are going to be considered

140
00:08:18,596 --> 00:08:21,879
I'll talk about software patents later,

141
00:08:22,199 --> 00:08:24,381
but there's always going to be an issue.

142
00:08:24,581 --> 00:08:26,122
Mechanics are never going to be copyrightable

143
00:08:26,162 --> 00:08:29,585
because they are a method, they are a process,

144
00:08:29,625 --> 00:08:31,306
they are something that is useful.

145
00:08:33,028 --> 00:08:36,731
But the creative elements, the characters, your story,

146
00:08:37,491 --> 00:08:39,813
the world you create, the music that you use,

147
00:08:40,334 --> 00:08:42,255
these are things that are going to be copyrightable

148
00:08:42,275 --> 00:08:45,238
and they kind of make your work distinct.

149
00:08:47,820 --> 00:08:49,741
and they give you the copyright protection that you want.

150
00:08:50,821 --> 00:08:57,143
So what is copyright infringement? There are a few forms of infringement, and the requirements

151
00:08:57,163 --> 00:09:01,785
that I have here are for direct infringement. But you also have contributory and vicarious

152
00:09:01,845 --> 00:09:07,287
infringement. A vicarious infringement typically revolves around having a financial stake in

153
00:09:07,327 --> 00:09:13,869
that infringement, and contributory infringement involves actively facilitating that infringement.

154
00:09:14,269 --> 00:09:16,270
So it's a slightly different standard from direct.

155
00:09:16,842 --> 00:09:19,844
The direct infringer is the one who's actually doing the copying.

156
00:09:20,285 --> 00:09:25,068
The vicarious and contributory infringers, I'm sure you guys have probably heard of Napster

157
00:09:25,108 --> 00:09:25,789
and Grokster.

158
00:09:26,189 --> 00:09:27,690
That's where we hear about these things.

159
00:09:29,071 --> 00:09:33,435
That's where you're going to have your vicarious and contributory infringement.

160
00:09:37,979 --> 00:09:41,140
So what are the rights you get whenever you get a copyright?

161
00:09:41,200 --> 00:09:43,481
Because it's not something, it's not a property right.

162
00:09:43,621 --> 00:09:44,121
Well, it is.

163
00:09:44,521 --> 00:09:46,542
But it's not a physical property right.

164
00:09:46,662 --> 00:09:48,442
It's not like you get a deed or a title.

165
00:09:49,343 --> 00:09:51,984
It's not something that you can physically take a hold

166
00:09:52,044 --> 00:09:52,984
of and carry with you.

167
00:09:53,824 --> 00:09:58,386
It's intangible, which is a problem in a lot of cases.

168
00:09:58,486 --> 00:10:00,326
Because unless you have some record

169
00:10:00,506 --> 00:10:05,468
of that intellectual property, it's difficult to prove.

170
00:10:07,403 --> 00:10:12,625
So as far as the rights that you get, obviously the right to reproduce, the one thing that

171
00:10:12,665 --> 00:10:16,326
I really want you to take away here, apart from derivative works, just be mindful of

172
00:10:16,366 --> 00:10:20,188
what a derivative work is, is moral rights and author's rights.

173
00:10:20,728 --> 00:10:25,230
And I say that because they are not commercial and they tie directly to the author.

174
00:10:25,710 --> 00:10:30,452
So even if you have a work for hire agreement, for instance, if you're outsourcing to a

175
00:10:31,328 --> 00:10:37,950
another company to do some work product for you, or if you are contracting with an independent

176
00:10:37,970 --> 00:10:46,773
contractor based out of Europe, there are going to be a body of rights that those individuals

177
00:10:46,813 --> 00:10:50,334
have that even if they have a work for hire agreement with you, which is something that

178
00:10:50,374 --> 00:10:57,536
we go into in licensing, you can't get rid of those rights. They're difficult to...

179
00:10:58,888 --> 00:11:01,290
to wave away, they're difficult to push away in any way.

180
00:11:01,310 --> 00:11:05,494
So you need to have some sort of workaround in your agreements

181
00:11:06,374 --> 00:11:11,578
that deals with those rights and how to address them

182
00:11:11,638 --> 00:11:14,641
so that they can't come back later on and tell you, OK,

183
00:11:14,681 --> 00:11:19,484
well, we want you to pull this because we feel that it does not

184
00:11:19,645 --> 00:11:22,947
adequately represent what we wanted to create.

185
00:11:27,430 --> 00:11:28,531
So a couple of notes.

186
00:11:29,292 --> 00:11:29,972
Defenses.

187
00:11:29,992 --> 00:11:34,835
I don't harp a lot on this because at the end of the day,

188
00:11:35,536 --> 00:11:37,397
you have to bear in mind that it's a defense, which means

189
00:11:37,417 --> 00:11:38,778
that somebody has to sue you first.

190
00:11:39,098 --> 00:11:41,860
And ideally, if you're a developer, you don't want it

191
00:11:41,880 --> 00:11:43,181
to ever get to that point.

192
00:11:44,562 --> 00:11:47,164
You never want to be the target of a lawsuit.

193
00:11:47,484 --> 00:11:50,606
But as far as what defenses can be raised, as I said

194
00:11:50,666 --> 00:11:52,447
before, independent origin is a big one.

195
00:11:52,807 --> 00:11:56,070
Senate fair is kind of another thing that.

196
00:11:56,489 --> 00:12:01,430
you need to take into consideration. And that's something that's really, really common. It's

197
00:12:01,510 --> 00:12:07,972
kind of common to a genre. So the example that you might want to say is like a zombie

198
00:12:08,032 --> 00:12:14,214
horror flick and the way that zombies move and things like that can be considered

199
00:12:14,274 --> 00:12:21,336
Santa Fe. And that will take it outside of the scope of copyright protection.

200
00:12:22,676 --> 00:12:26,477
nominally uses whenever a use is so minuscule that it's not really an issue.

201
00:12:27,798 --> 00:12:29,058
And there are also exceptions.

202
00:12:29,138 --> 00:12:34,920
And every few years, the Copyright Office re-evaluates these exceptions and adds new

203
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:35,100
ones.

204
00:12:35,140 --> 00:12:39,121
And the most recent ones this year happen to be parity and private copies.

205
00:12:39,642 --> 00:12:44,303
Note that these were not in the actual DMCA until this year.

206
00:12:44,943 --> 00:12:50,545
So while these usually fell under the purview of fair use and could be raised as a defense,

207
00:12:51,060 --> 00:12:54,002
Now they fall squarely within the copyright exceptions,

208
00:12:54,042 --> 00:12:56,704
which means that you can't really bring a claim even

209
00:12:57,985 --> 00:13:01,228
if it qualifies as a parody or if it qualifies

210
00:13:01,308 --> 00:13:02,008
as a private copy.

211
00:13:02,348 --> 00:13:04,850
Now the problem with that is that what is a parody?

212
00:13:05,611 --> 00:13:10,775
And this is something that is highly disputed

213
00:13:11,355 --> 00:13:15,118
and it varies from country to country,

214
00:13:15,178 --> 00:13:17,620
from jurisdiction to jurisdiction, circuit to circuit.

215
00:13:19,854 --> 00:13:22,955
the EU standard of parodies is going to be very different from the

216
00:13:23,515 --> 00:13:26,556
United States standard of parodies because we have very different senses of humor.

217
00:13:28,577 --> 00:13:31,498
But, yeah, so

218
00:13:32,058 --> 00:13:35,559
again, this is where I have to say it depends. You don't know

219
00:13:35,679 --> 00:13:38,480
until it gets litigated.

220
00:13:41,181 --> 00:13:45,203
But it is a clearly stated exception now, so it's something that you can

221
00:13:46,437 --> 00:13:51,381
you know, take to the bank with you if you do plan on implementing parities and the way

222
00:13:51,401 --> 00:13:54,843
that you market your product or any way that you execute your product.

223
00:13:57,125 --> 00:13:58,446
Moving on, we've got trademarks.

224
00:14:00,788 --> 00:14:02,389
This is again the legal definition.

225
00:14:02,409 --> 00:14:03,490
I'm not going to recite it.

226
00:14:04,831 --> 00:14:07,953
The easiest way to understand trademarks

227
00:14:09,832 --> 00:14:15,114
said it is your brand. It is how you market yourself. It is how people identify you in

228
00:14:15,134 --> 00:14:22,677
the marketplace. It is your logo. It is the way that your goodwill is reflected on the

229
00:14:22,737 --> 00:14:30,100
world. And you have some examples here. Some really interesting examples are going to be

230
00:14:30,140 --> 00:14:34,621
things like sound marks, and those are really fun. I did a talk on that pretty recently,

231
00:14:34,922 --> 00:14:35,282
actually.

232
00:14:37,797 --> 00:14:42,501
It's interesting how much audio plays a role in how we recognize things.

233
00:14:42,702 --> 00:14:45,644
I had some examples like the Lord of the Rings music.

234
00:14:45,704 --> 00:14:47,766
Like, da, da, da, da, da, da.

235
00:14:47,806 --> 00:14:52,110
Things like that can qualify you for trademark protection.

236
00:14:52,250 --> 00:14:56,013
Some other things that are pretty useful are trade dress.

237
00:14:56,885 --> 00:15:00,406
And the cool thing about TradeDress, as far as your IP portfolio goes,

238
00:15:00,746 --> 00:15:02,467
is that it can cover a lot of things.

239
00:15:02,527 --> 00:15:04,708
It can cover the look and feel of your product,

240
00:15:05,368 --> 00:15:07,589
the types of colors that you use, like your color scheme,

241
00:15:07,889 --> 00:15:11,210
which may not be original enough to qualify for copyright protection.

