00:15:11,751 --> 00:15:13,771
It can qualify you for TradeDress.

243
00:15:14,332 --> 00:15:18,413
So I have... I represent a lot of app developers.

244
00:15:18,833 --> 00:15:21,534
I spent a lot of time representing app developers when I started out.

245
00:15:24,862 --> 00:15:26,503
A lot of apps are really, really simple.

246
00:15:27,303 --> 00:15:28,324
Like, stupidly simple.

247
00:15:29,084 --> 00:15:30,765
But they're a lot of fun and people like them.

248
00:15:31,245 --> 00:15:33,887
And they are very easy to infringe upon.

249
00:15:34,367 --> 00:15:37,749
And you can't always claim copyright protection

250
00:15:37,769 --> 00:15:38,389
to some of this stuff.

251
00:15:38,409 --> 00:15:40,710
Because sometimes the only thing they seem to claim

252
00:15:41,271 --> 00:15:43,392
are going to be the mechanics and maybe

253
00:15:43,452 --> 00:15:47,214
some of the look and feel elements, like the UI.

254
00:15:48,162 --> 00:15:53,905
Trade dress is a very good idea, and trademark and unfair competition law is a very good

255
00:15:53,985 --> 00:15:59,729
way to protect those particular elements that fall outside of copyright protection, but

256
00:15:59,769 --> 00:16:02,851
you still want to be able to send a cease and desist letter out for.

257
00:16:06,733 --> 00:16:13,297
So what is the trademark infringement standard? I also want to point out that trademarks don't

258
00:16:13,337 --> 00:16:17,180
really have a term. They exist for as long as you use them.

259
00:16:17,590 --> 00:16:18,850
Now they can be abandoned.

260
00:16:19,470 --> 00:16:23,192
And the typical term for abandonment is three to five

261
00:16:23,252 --> 00:16:23,532
years.

262
00:16:23,652 --> 00:16:25,512
And I'm not saying this just for the US.

263
00:16:25,552 --> 00:16:27,233
That is internationally.

264
00:16:28,834 --> 00:16:30,214
Egypt, I think, is five years.

265
00:16:30,354 --> 00:16:33,235
But most other countries are about three to five.

266
00:16:35,096 --> 00:16:38,397
So abandonment just means that you're not using it

267
00:16:38,437 --> 00:16:39,057
in commerce.

268
00:16:39,597 --> 00:16:41,718
And token uses don't qualify.

269
00:16:41,738 --> 00:16:44,059
So you actually have to be actively using your brand

270
00:16:44,139 --> 00:16:46,920
in commerce for it to qualify for trademark protection.

271
00:16:47,280 --> 00:16:55,027
It's actually something that is going back as far as what it is.

272
00:16:56,588 --> 00:17:02,533
The really important thing to note about trademarks is that you actually have to be using it in

273
00:17:02,693 --> 00:17:03,213
commerce.

274
00:17:03,814 --> 00:17:08,177
And whether that means you're using it to market your product, you have to be selling

275
00:17:08,238 --> 00:17:09,819
something under it, essentially.

276
00:17:10,079 --> 00:17:15,403
And that doesn't necessarily mean that you have to earn a profit.

277
00:17:16,582 --> 00:17:17,283
A lot of people don't.

278
00:17:17,523 --> 00:17:19,823
It also doesn't mean that it doesn't apply to non-profits

279
00:17:19,863 --> 00:17:20,564
and things like that.

280
00:17:21,784 --> 00:17:23,125
When I say selling, it means that it

281
00:17:23,165 --> 00:17:25,345
has to be generating some kind of goodwill.

282
00:17:26,866 --> 00:17:29,327
That's how I like to think about it in terms of actually

283
00:17:29,387 --> 00:17:31,668
procuring trademark protection.

284
00:17:32,188 --> 00:17:35,269
Even if you're not receiving income from it right now,

285
00:17:35,349 --> 00:17:38,870
so long as you are marketing a product or service that

286
00:17:38,930 --> 00:17:41,411
is generating goodwill and that is generating

287
00:17:46,825 --> 00:17:50,927
connection with your product or the thing that you're doing, that can qualify you for

288
00:17:50,967 --> 00:17:57,611
trademark protection. So just registering your logo without actually using it or without

289
00:17:57,691 --> 00:18:02,674
actually creating that brand and marketing and creating that affiliation between your

290
00:18:02,714 --> 00:18:07,577
product and the logo isn't going to be sufficient. And I'll talk about registration here in a

291
00:18:07,597 --> 00:18:14,681
bit. So what is trademark infringement? Like copyright infringement, it does kind of have

292
00:18:14,741 --> 00:18:16,442
a strict liability element to it.

293
00:18:17,024 --> 00:18:19,785
And that is the likelihood of confusion standard.

294
00:18:20,085 --> 00:18:24,047
So even if you're not intending to infringe on somebody's mark,

295
00:18:25,388 --> 00:18:30,071
you can still be prohibited from using your own mark in commerce

296
00:18:30,551 --> 00:18:33,573
because it creates that likelihood of confusion.

297
00:18:34,213 --> 00:18:35,954
And what that typically means is,

298
00:18:36,294 --> 00:18:40,176
would the ordinary consumer look at those two brands,

299
00:18:40,537 --> 00:18:43,838
like look at two competing brands or two brands that are

300
00:18:45,337 --> 00:18:48,798
in a related marketplace or competitors,

301
00:18:49,118 --> 00:18:50,259
would they be confused?

302
00:18:50,839 --> 00:18:53,880
And this kind of, it is not related,

303
00:18:53,900 --> 00:18:57,201
it is not limited to strictly competing marks, right?

304
00:18:58,322 --> 00:19:02,584
Anything that qualifies as like a related class

305
00:19:03,024 --> 00:19:03,964
can create that problem.

306
00:19:04,404 --> 00:19:06,505
And now when we're talking about famous marks,

307
00:19:06,525 --> 00:19:08,206
when we're talking about Sony,

308
00:19:08,266 --> 00:19:10,047
when we're talking about Coca-Cola,

309
00:19:10,407 --> 00:19:11,667
when we're talking about Pepsi.

310
00:19:13,768 --> 00:19:16,871
you have this other element of dilution and tarnishment.

311
00:19:17,571 --> 00:19:20,153
And dilution comes into play whenever,

312
00:19:20,173 --> 00:19:22,535
even if it's not in a related market,

313
00:19:22,956 --> 00:19:25,898
if you use the brand name, it can be prohibited.

314
00:19:27,840 --> 00:19:29,361
And tarnishment is obviously, you know,

315
00:19:29,381 --> 00:19:31,923
certain kinds of disparagement or associating a product,

316
00:19:32,324 --> 00:19:34,846
associating a brand with a product

317
00:19:34,866 --> 00:19:38,409
that might create some kind of disparagement

318
00:19:38,429 --> 00:19:40,330
to that product or to that brand.

319
00:19:43,417 --> 00:19:45,298
Trademark law is not limited to just trademarks.

320
00:19:45,498 --> 00:19:46,458
It's part of the Lanham Act.

321
00:19:47,559 --> 00:19:53,802
And so it also implies certain levels of unfair competition.

322
00:19:54,163 --> 00:19:57,124
Unfair competition is exactly what it sounds like.

323
00:19:57,965 --> 00:20:09,551
It is some kind of fraud, some kind of implicitly wrong act.

324
00:20:09,571 --> 00:20:11,992
And while there are legal standards to this,

325
00:20:12,445 --> 00:20:13,706
It is kind of vague.

326
00:20:13,746 --> 00:20:16,507
It is kind of somewhat open-ended as far

327
00:20:16,807 --> 00:20:18,588
as what constitutes as unfair.

328
00:20:18,888 --> 00:20:20,748
There are obviously some standards.

329
00:20:20,849 --> 00:20:24,070
It can't just be ordinarily, like the things that

330
00:20:24,110 --> 00:20:26,331
happen during the ordinary course of business

331
00:20:26,351 --> 00:20:27,971
and ordinary course of competition.

332
00:20:27,991 --> 00:20:30,092
It has to be kind of a step up above that,

333
00:20:31,112 --> 00:20:35,534
whether it be openly disparaging your competitor in a way

334
00:20:35,594 --> 00:20:38,995
that is untruthful.

335
00:20:39,638 --> 00:20:43,761
For example, any kind of fraud is obviously going to implicate unfair competition.

336
00:20:44,321 --> 00:20:47,223
And then obviously, counterfeiting goods, counterfeiting marks.

337
00:20:47,623 --> 00:20:52,246
And I raise unfair competition because the Trademark Act only applies to registered marks.

338
00:20:52,626 --> 00:20:55,688
So you don't get full trademark protection unless you've registered.

339
00:21:01,252 --> 00:21:02,493
Now moving on to patents.

340
00:21:03,253 --> 00:21:04,774
There are three different types of patents.

341
00:21:05,278 --> 00:21:09,479
the only ones that we really pay attention to are utility and design because plant patents

342
00:21:09,679 --> 00:21:15,121
literally mean physical plants. I don't know, well, plants versus zombies would not apply.

343
00:21:17,621 --> 00:21:23,743
But utility and design patents are very, very relevant to the games industry. We see a lot

344
00:21:23,783 --> 00:21:31,005
of litigation coming out from various big names concerning utility patents, controllers,

345
00:21:31,065 --> 00:21:32,685
any kind of hardware that people develop.

346
00:21:34,432 --> 00:21:38,633
Design patents less so. A lot of people don't go in for design patents because there is

347
00:21:38,733 --> 00:21:43,975
considerable overlap between design patents and copyright and trademark. It kind of protects

348
00:21:43,995 --> 00:21:52,318
some of the same elements and some of the same infringement standards are used. So trademark

349
00:21:52,358 --> 00:21:59,921
protection and design patents do tend to overlap a lot. Not many patent attorneys that I know

350
00:22:00,041 --> 00:22:00,442
generally

351
00:22:00,892 --> 00:22:05,014
go into recommending design patents unless there is a pressing reason to do so.

352
00:22:07,856 --> 00:22:15,660
Utility patents, on the other hand, are very important, not just if you decide to go into

353
00:22:15,680 --> 00:22:19,863
the business or if you are in the business of developing hardware, but also if you are

354
00:22:19,943 --> 00:22:25,026
licensing hardware or if you are in the business of manufacturing such things.

355
00:22:28,742 --> 00:22:29,682
It has to be useful.

356
00:22:31,063 --> 00:22:33,185
Business methods actually are patentable.

357
00:22:34,206 --> 00:22:36,408
So are, to some extent, software patents.

358
00:22:36,488 --> 00:22:37,949
And I'm going to go into that here in a bit.

359
00:22:39,090 --> 00:22:41,592
But the key elements is that it has to be new.

360
00:22:42,553 --> 00:22:45,875
It can't be something that's been created before.

361
00:22:46,276 --> 00:22:49,878
It has to be non-obvious to a person in that field.

362
00:22:50,399 --> 00:22:51,139
And it has to be useful.

363
00:22:51,920 --> 00:22:55,363
So anything that is patentable is not

364
00:22:55,403 --> 00:22:56,764
copyrightable, and vice versa.

365
00:22:57,589 --> 00:22:59,291
Those two are mutually exclusive.

366
00:23:01,515 --> 00:23:06,944
And I don't think the term for utility patents has changed.

367
00:23:07,024 --> 00:23:09,268
The term for design patents has, however.

368
00:23:09,909 --> 00:23:10,570
It used to be.

369
00:23:12,342 --> 00:23:16,604
14 years. It was 14 years for quite some time, and just recently they added a year.

370
00:23:16,784 --> 00:23:21,847
And I could not begin to tell you why. Just a heads up, we don't do a lot of patent work.

371
00:23:22,487 --> 00:23:27,650
I have a sociology, social psychology double major, so I never will unless I go back to school.

372
00:23:28,971 --> 00:23:32,913
But you have to have a scientific background in order to do that.

373
00:23:37,294 --> 00:23:42,058
But I do have enough understanding to tell you when you might need a patent and when

374
00:23:42,098 --> 00:23:50,284
patent infringement might be an issue.

375
00:23:50,925 --> 00:23:56,789
There are some differences, at least as far as copyright goes, for a design patent.

376
00:23:56,889 --> 00:24:01,913
A lot like trademark, it is strict liability, but also it doesn't require access, which

377
00:24:01,993 --> 00:24:03,655
is another element of the trademark thing.

378
00:24:03,675 --> 00:24:06,817
They more overlap with trademark than with patent.

379
00:24:07,268 --> 00:24:22,194
Copyright. I'll give you some time to read this because it's kind of dense.

380
00:24:23,175 --> 00:24:33,779
This is probably the most contentious issue for patent law in our industry. Software problems

381
00:24:33,919 --> 00:24:35,620
are kind of problematic.

382
00:24:37,038 --> 00:24:43,503
And it's not always easy to tell when a software patent applies.

383
00:24:43,884 --> 00:24:47,827
I don't really want to spend a lot of time talking about this, because this in and of

384
00:24:47,867 --> 00:24:49,568
itself is worth a talk.

385
00:24:51,169 --> 00:24:54,232
And I just don't have time to start going down this road.

386
00:24:54,432 --> 00:25:01,798
But if you do have questions about the software patent issue, obviously after the talk, whenever

387
00:25:01,838 --> 00:25:03,700
we have some questions, you can raise those.

388
00:25:06,958 --> 00:25:08,579
So what is patent infringement?

389
00:25:08,819 --> 00:25:11,059
Again, you kind of have the strict liability thing.

390
00:25:11,299 --> 00:25:15,020
What I mean by strict liability is that it's not intentional.

391
00:25:15,840 --> 00:25:19,601
A lot of federal, a lot of criminal claims,

392
00:25:19,621 --> 00:25:24,622
a lot of tortious claims, all of those require intent.

393
00:25:25,522 --> 00:25:28,003
You have to have a certain mindfulness to do that.

394
00:25:28,303 --> 00:25:29,843
Now, mindfulness does come into play,

395
00:25:29,943 --> 00:25:32,644
or being aware of the infringement

396
00:25:32,684 --> 00:25:34,344
does come into play whenever.

397
00:25:35,568 --> 00:25:41,769
you know what you're doing is wrong and you're doing it, you know, you're doing it in bad

398
00:25:41,809 --> 00:25:47,710
faith because it plays into damages. A lot of courts are obviously going to award punitive

399
00:25:47,750 --> 00:25:54,751
damages in the event that you are acting in bad faith. You can limit your, while it is

400
00:25:54,791 --> 00:25:59,472
a strict liability tort and you know you can get injunctions imposed against you from doing

401
00:25:59,492 --> 00:26:04,433
it, you can limit the harm to yourself by showing that you know it was an accident.

402
00:26:04,964 --> 00:26:07,205
officer I didn't mean to just be that.

403
00:26:14,387 --> 00:26:15,447
Okay, so moving on.

404
00:26:17,167 --> 00:26:18,128
Personality rights.

405
00:26:20,468 --> 00:26:20,908
This is

406
00:26:22,069 --> 00:26:26,550
kind of a fun area of the law because again it is kind of a

407
00:26:27,610 --> 00:26:30,871
it depends thing it literally changes from state to state

408
00:26:31,531 --> 00:26:32,211
and not just

409
00:26:34,573 --> 00:26:37,234
I mean, just the names of whether or not,

410
00:26:37,294 --> 00:26:38,954
like name and likeness and appropriation,

411
00:26:39,315 --> 00:26:40,215
totally interchangeable.

412
00:26:40,515 --> 00:26:41,475
Depends on the state you're in.

413
00:26:44,396 --> 00:26:45,536
Right of privacy less so.

414
00:26:45,636 --> 00:26:48,397
Intrusion is kind of self-explanatory.

415
00:26:50,297 --> 00:26:53,918
There are a few overlaps, but actually very careful

416
00:26:53,958 --> 00:26:57,019
distinctions between things like public disclosure

417
00:26:57,119 --> 00:27:00,699
of private facts and false light, defamation.

418
00:27:00,719 --> 00:27:04,380
A lot of it comes down to whether there is economic harm.

419
00:27:05,803 --> 00:27:10,165
A lot of it comes down to whether it is more injury to the individual from a psychological

420
00:27:10,205 --> 00:27:10,725
standpoint.

421
00:27:12,006 --> 00:27:16,428
And that's kind of the difference between publicity rights and privacy rights in general.

422
00:27:16,489 --> 00:27:19,890
Publicity rights are almost exclusively economic and commercial.

423
00:27:20,311 --> 00:27:26,494
Privacy rights are almost exclusively, you should really hurt my feelings and you know,

424
00:27:26,974 --> 00:27:33,358
you caused me a lot of personal harm, caused me a lot of psychological damage.

425
00:27:36,068 --> 00:27:40,329
As far as publicity rights go, when I say it's commercial, I mean that the person,

426
00:27:41,789 --> 00:27:43,230
their stock and trade is their name.

427
00:27:43,950 --> 00:27:48,051
You have like celebrities are a great example where a name and likeness issue comes up.

428
00:27:48,791 --> 00:27:55,393
I actually was speaking with somebody yesterday about the Lindsay Lohanhan GTA case

429
00:27:55,513 --> 00:28:01,095
where she's claiming that her name and likeness is being used in that game.

430
00:28:03,735 --> 00:28:05,196
As far as raising the defamation...

431
00:28:05,758 --> 00:28:11,021
issue, there's always defamation-proof characters and we have an example of one right there.

432
00:28:15,562 --> 00:28:24,126
But what is defamation? The biggest thing I want you to take away from defamation is

433
00:28:24,286 --> 00:28:30,868
one, it has to actually be published. It's not something that you say to that person.

434
00:28:31,429 --> 00:28:34,850
It has to be something that you share with third parties. It has to be something that

435
00:28:34,870 --> 00:28:35,430
you publish.

436
00:28:37,592 --> 00:28:42,215
Another thing is, it has to be stated as a fact, so it can't just be your opinion.

437
00:28:42,455 --> 00:28:47,397
You can have a really negative opinion about somebody, you can say some horrendous things

438
00:28:47,577 --> 00:28:55,361
about another human being, provided you don't move into the threat category.

439
00:28:57,425 --> 00:28:59,647
you can say some terrible things about another person,

440
00:28:59,887 --> 00:29:04,389
and so long as it's couched in the form of an opinion,

441
00:29:04,749 --> 00:29:06,490
there's very little anybody can do about it.

442
00:29:07,271 --> 00:29:11,433
Now, if you imply anything that even touches on a possible fact

443
00:29:11,953 --> 00:29:13,534
or assumes that something is true,

444
00:29:14,114 --> 00:29:15,275
then you trigger defamation.

445
00:29:15,295 --> 00:29:17,316
So that's something that you need to be careful of.

446
00:29:17,816 --> 00:29:21,138
And this isn't limited to just how you say it,

447
00:29:21,198 --> 00:29:22,799
because this isn't just limited to words.

448
00:29:23,139 --> 00:29:24,640
It's how you portray people.

449
00:29:25,120 --> 00:29:26,341
So if you're using a...

450
00:29:27,262 --> 00:29:32,306
a particular likeness of somebody in your game and you are portraying that likeness

451
00:29:32,366 --> 00:29:42,535
or that parody of a person in a way that implies that that person is actually like that to

452
00:29:42,555 --> 00:29:48,921
an extent that it is disparaging, it can create some kind of commercial or psychological harm,

453
00:29:51,323 --> 00:29:54,206
you run the risk of being the target of a defamation suit.

454
00:29:55,673 --> 00:29:58,835
Honestly, the threshold issue is if they are pissed off enough

455
00:29:59,175 --> 00:30:00,936
to bring a legal claim against you,

456
00:30:02,036 --> 00:30:03,277
it's already kind of a problem.

457
00:30:03,537 --> 00:30:06,439
As I said, while you can't always be risk averse,

458
00:30:08,140 --> 00:30:11,601
to the extent that you can limit creating

459
00:30:11,621 --> 00:30:14,603
these issues for yourself, you should.

460
00:30:16,044 --> 00:30:17,725
There are defenses, obviously.

461
00:30:18,025 --> 00:30:21,387
Truth, to that extent, the whole defamation proof thing

462
00:30:21,627 --> 00:30:22,147
comes up.

463
00:30:22,887 --> 00:30:24,488
If somebody really is a horrible person.

464
00:30:25,163 --> 00:30:27,524
And they have done horrible things, and you can show that.

465
00:30:28,385 --> 00:30:29,965
Well, not much you can do about it.

466
00:30:31,866 --> 00:30:33,227
Also, consent.

467
00:30:33,387 --> 00:30:34,868
Consent is kind of a tricky issue,

468
00:30:34,908 --> 00:30:37,349
because what constitutes consent?

469
00:30:37,809 --> 00:30:43,052
If somebody gives you a license to use their name and likeness,

470
00:30:43,652 --> 00:30:47,934
how far can you go with that as far as a defamation claim is

471
00:30:47,974 --> 00:30:48,435
concerned?

472
00:30:48,855 --> 00:30:51,196
So that's something that you need to take into consideration

473
00:30:51,256 --> 00:30:51,716
as well.

474
00:30:54,398 --> 00:30:54,798
Accident.

475
00:30:56,412 --> 00:30:58,874
Kind of a trickier issue in and of itself,

476
00:30:58,934 --> 00:31:01,737
just because how do you prove that it's an accident?

477
00:31:01,797 --> 00:31:04,659
I mean, you're saying, how do you

478
00:31:04,719 --> 00:31:10,564
show that you did not know that it was false, right?

479
00:31:11,545 --> 00:31:12,786
How do you show goodwill?

480
00:31:15,048 --> 00:31:15,788
And then privilege.

481
00:31:16,529 --> 00:31:18,450
People like me can pretty much get away

482
00:31:18,490 --> 00:31:20,052
with it whenever we're dealing with a court proceeding.

483
00:31:20,492 --> 00:31:22,233
But otherwise, privilege is pretty limited.

484
00:31:26,250 --> 00:31:28,932
So trade secrets.

